[SN]TITLE[SN]
Greek woes depress FTSE 100 further

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
(Close): London shares continued their downward slide as fears over Greece's ability to negotiate a settlement with European creditors dented sentiment.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
At the close, the benchmark FTSE 100 index was down 61.82 points, or 0.9%, at 6,784.92.
The top riser was Royal Mail, up 2.78%, recouping some of Thursday's losses.
The postal services company had fallen 4.5% on news that the government had sold 15% of its remaining 30% stake in the company, raising Â£750m.
The biggest faller on the 100-share index was Johnson Matthey, down 3.1%.
On the FTSE 250, platinum producer Lonmin fell 7.1%, compounding earlier losses in the week, after mining and commodity firm Glencore distributed its 23.9% stake in the company to investors.
Glencore had inherited the stake in Lonmin after buying miner Xstrata in 2013.
